%I A395747 #24 May 13 2026 09:28:45
%S A395747 4,1,6,1,2,3,1,1,3,1,2,8,2,7,7,2,2,7,6,7,5,2
%N A395747 Initial digit of the decimal expansion of 2^(2^(2^n)).
%C A395747 a(n) is the leading (decimal) digit of 2^2^2^n and, according to the Googology user Allam948736, the sequence would continue with 7, 2, 7, 2, 1, 3, 3, 9, ... (see Links).
%C A395747 Among the first 22 terms, the distribution of leading digits is broadly consistent with Benford's law. For instance, the digit 1 occurs 6 times (about 27.3 percent), close to the expected log_10(2), whereas the digit 7 occurs 4 times (about 18.2 percent) instead of log_10(8/7); given the small sample size, such fluctuations are not unexpected.
%H A395747 Googology, <a href="https://googology.fandom.com/wiki/Tetration">Tetration</a>
%H A395747 Googology, <a href="https://googology.fandom.com/wiki/User:Allam948736">Googology User Allam948736</a>
%H A395747 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/BenfordsLaw.html">Benford's Law</a>
%H A395747 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PowerTower.html">Power Tower</a>
%F A395747 For n >= 0, a(n) = A000030(2^(2^(2^n))).
%e A395747 a(0) = 4, since 2^(2^(2^0)) = 2^2 = 4.
%e A395747 a(1) = 1, since 2^(2^(2^1)) = 2^4 = 16.
%o A395747 (Python)
%o A395747 import mpmath as mp
%o A395747 def a(n):
%o A395747     if n==0:return 4
%o A395747     e=2**n
%o A395747     E=2**e
%o A395747     mp.mp.dps=int(e*mp.log10(2))+40
%o A395747     x=mp.mpf(E)*mp.log10(2)
%o A395747     f=x-mp.floor(x)
%o A395747     return int(mp.floor(mp.power(10,f)))
%o A395747 n=0
%o A395747 while True:
%o A395747     print(f"a({n}) = {a(n)}")
%o A395747     n+=1
%o A395747 (PARI) a(n)= localprec(2^n); 10^(2^(2^n)*log(2)/log(10)%1)\1; \\ _Ruud H.G. van Tol_, May 11 2026
%Y A395747 Cf. A000030, A241291, A241299, A244059, A362004, A395745.
